URGENT: Gary police are searching for a missing teen missing since early Monday who they say may be in extreme danger.

Chastinea Reeves, 15, went missing at 2 a.m., police said. She was last seen in the area of 2027 Maine St. in Gary wearing a gray shirt and light-colored jeans. She is described as 5 feet, 2 inches and 130 pounds, with black hair and brown eyes.

Anyone with information about her whereabouts is asked to contact Detective Kristopher Adams at 219-755-3855, central dispatch at 219-660-0000 or 911.
link_name: Missing Gary teen may be in extreme danger

Opening reception for "Small But Mighty" art exhibit. "Small But Mighty" runs through Jan. 26 in the Christopher Art Gallery at Prairie State College in Chicago Heights, featuring more than 30 works by artists from as far away as California, New York, Missouri, Ohio and Wisconsin and as close as Crete. Juror Aron Packer selected from over 300 works by more than 100 artists. The show includes freestanding ceramic sculptures, relief, paintings, drawings, mixed media, fiber and collage with works ranging from hyper-realistic to very abstract.

[Photos by Tony V. Martin]

Mick Cornett, President of The United States Conference of Mayors will be the keynote speaker at the Sept. 15th One Region luncheon. Cornett has served as Mayor of Oklahoma City since March 2004. His most notable achievements as Mayor include his leadership in attracting  the city's first major league sports team and the passage of MAPS 3, a $777 million quality-of-life infrastructure program. Cornett is a proponent of issues such as rapid and mass transit, economic diversification, urban renaissance and civic beautification.

Please join us for our Annual Awards Luncheon Sept. 15 at the Radisson Star Plaza. This year's keynote speaker is Mayor Mick Cornett, of Oklahoma City, who will share with us how he improved the city's quality of place to stimulate economic activity. Newsweek magazine called him one of the "five most innovative Mayors in the United States."  Politico placed him on the publication's Politico 50 list of "thinkers, doers and visionaries transforming American politics in 2015."

One Region will honor individuals who have made a significant contribution to the quality of life in Northwest Indiana. 

We hope you will be able to join us for this annual event. Space is limited, so early registration is recommended.

Please join us for our Annual Awards Luncheon on Thursday, September 15, 2016 at the Radisson Star Plaza in Merrillville, IN. This year's keynote speaker is Mayor Mick Cornett of Oklahoma City who will share with us how he improved the city's quality of place to stimulate economic activity. Newsweek magazine called him one of the "five most innovative Mayors in the United States."  Politico placed him on the publication's Politico 50 list of "thinkers, doers and visionaries transforming American politics in 2015."

One Region will honor individuals who have made a significant contribution to the quality of life in Northwest Indiana.

We hope you will be able to join us for this annual event.  Space is limited, so early registration is recommended.

Go to oneregionnwi.org/register to order tickets.

Pink Ribbon Society is looking for "Calendar Girls or Guys.  If you know an individual who is a breast cancer survivor and you think they would make a great role model for others diagnosed with breast cancer, nominate them to appear in the 2017 Breast Cancer Survivors' Calendar that is published annually by the Pink Ribbon Society.

Send us information about this person:  their name, year of diagnosis, personal and/or professional accomplishments, and the things in general that you think make them outstanding.

You can nominate your mom, dad, daughter, son, sister, brother, co-worker, friend or anyone that you think would be considered a role model for others in our community whose lives have been touched by breast cancer.

Send your nominations to Pink Ribbon Society, 11011 Allendale Court, Crown Point, IN 46307.  You can also submit your nomination to our e-mail at www.prs4990@yahoo.com…..make sure you indicate "calendar girl nomination" in the subject area.

For more info go to http://pinkribbonsociety.org/calendar-guys-and-girls-wanted/

Deadline for nominations is July 1, 2016

Artworks by 44 area high school students, on display now through March 11 in the Gallery for Contemporary Art at Indiana University Northwest.

 This year's exhibiting schools include: 21st Century Charter of Gary, Andrean, Bishop Noll Institute, Boone Grove, Chesterton, Crown Point, George Rogers Clark, Griffith, Hanover Central, Hebron, Highland, Hobart, Lake Central, Lighthouse College Prep Charter School in Gary, Merrillville, Munster, Portage, River Forest, Valparaiso, Westside, and Wirt/Emerson. 

A reception is planned in the gallery from 5 to 7 p.m., Wednesday, Feb. 24.

The Gallery for Contemporary Art is located in the Savannah Center. Hours are Monday and Thursday from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Tuesday and Wednesday from 9 a.m. to 7 p.m. and Friday from 9 a.m. to 3 p.m.

status_message:
Power was restored to about 2,600 Kankakee Valley REMC customers in Porter County on Monday night after a utility pole fire in the Valparaiso area, spokeswoman Amanda Steeb said. Kankakee Valley REMC's transmission provider, NIPSCO, had to cut power to the cooperative's Morgan Township substation to safely make repairs, she said. Customers in Center, Morgan and Porter townships lost power about 6 p.m.

NIPSCO customers in the Valparaiso area experienced flickering lights Monday, but the company reported no electrical outages, spokesman Larry Graham said. 

The fire in this video was observed on a utility pole near Elm and Locust streets in Valparaiso.

status_message: "I had a situation with a Latin kid who was in a gang. He was trying to impress all the gang members and his family was just fed up with him because he was out there shooting, he was gang-banging, he was doing everything that his parents didn't want. But when I met this young man for the first time I kind of stood off to the side while other officers were talking down to him. Everyone was attacking him and I thought, 'Nobody's talking good to him, I'm gonna go over and do that.' When they were done I said 'Let me talk to you. What's going on with you? Tell me your side of the story.' We built a friendship and I got to visiting him at his house several times. He didn't really change after that first conversation, but after that second or third time, and him seeing me keeping my word about coming back to the house, it changed him. I said, 'It's not too late to be something different. Family's always first. When those guys you're hanging with leave you, you'll have to come back home. They're the ones who'll open their door for you.' He needed someone to respond to him and give him positive reinforcement. That's all he needed. He turned around. He's not even gang-banging anymore. He's at Ivy Tech now, learning a trade." E.C. Officer Will Askew. Read the story: http://bit.ly/1FtT8iU.

status_message:
Great news for the #CivilityCounts campaign! Tomorrow, past and present Northwest Indiana professional sports figures will share their perspectives about the importance of education and civility to around 1,100 middle school and high school students from Hammond, East Chicago and Gary at a program called "Education Matters #CivilityCounts: Be About that Life" at Purdue University Calumet. 
Speaking will be Kawann Short Gives Back (pictured), defensive tackle for the Carolina Panthers, former Purdue University standout and East Chicago native; Wallace Johnson, former major league baseball player/coach and Gary native; and Greg Tagert, manager of the Gary SouthShore RailCats. 
The Times will be there for full scale coverage, look for the story tomorrow. And stay involved by liking the Civility Counts Facebook page!

status_message:
VALPARAISO | Tickets go on sale at 8 a.m. Monday for Natalie Cole's performance at Valparaiso University's 30th Annual Jazz Festival set for April 11. About 2,000 tickets will be available on a first-come, first-served basis and will cost $15 for VU students and $30 to $75 for the general public.

Cole has won multiple Grammy Awards and will perform for approximately 75 minutes in the university's Athletic Recreation Center beginning at 8:30 p.m. Tickets may be purchased at the ARC's Box Office from 10 a.m through 4 p.m., or online at www.valpo.edu/jazz-fest-tickets/.

status_message:
The Times Media Co, has unveiled a new program to recognize top high school juniors and seniors who excel in and out of the classroom. It's called Rising Stars of the Region and we're now accepting nominations.

Download the nomination form at www.nwi.com/risingstars. If you know a top student in your community, make sure he or she knows about this.

Nominations must be received by March 2. We'll form a panel of judges to review the nominations and select 15 Rising Stars of the Region. Every nomination form must be signed by a teacher and must include letters of recommendation, including one from a teacher, school counselor or principal.

The 15 Rising Stars selected will be recognized in May. This program, however, will continue with a monthly selection and recognition of a Rising Star, starting in June. We'll reopen the application process after the first group is named.

Rising Stars of the Region will deserve your applause. Join us in getting the word out.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message:
Apply Now!

Distribution Center Drivers
 
The Times newspaper has several positions available for responsible, customer-focused people to deliver our print products as we bring this part of our operations in house. These positions are critical to providing premier service to our carriers and our Times readers.
 
We will be hiring Full Time, Regular Part Time (30-39 hours) and Part Time (20-29 hours).  Please state your hours preference in your application.
 
Duties include pick-up and delivery of newspapers to distribution centers for independent contractor pick-up. In addition, the distribution center driver will deliver Pre-prints, TMC, and niche products throughout the market and to distribution centers. Newspaper delivery shifts start at 11:00 PM and are usually 6 -- 8 hours a day. Niche, Pre-print, and TMC delivery hours are in addition to this.
 
We need reliable people with a valid driver's license, proof of insurability, good driving record, knowledge and ability to operate a fork lift and pellet jack, and to lift up to 50 lbs.    A pre-employment drug and background screen and MVR is also required.
 
We offer an excellent benefits package and paid time off. 
 
Interested and qualified individuals may apply on line at 

nwi.com/timesjobs.

2014 Hometown Holiday Celebration begins Nov. 29th
Celebrate the holidays with your Duneland community this year during the 2014 Hometown Holiday Celebration!

Saturday, November 29th:

3-5pm
Free horse-drawn carriage rides through downtown Chesterton
Rides begin along Broadway in the Chesterton/Duneland Chamber of Commerce parking lot.

4pm-7pm
Piping hot chocolate beginning at 4pm
Support your local businesses by purchasing hot chocolate as you enjoy the Parade! The hot chocolate tent will be located in the Chamber parking lot.

5:30pm
The Annual Twilight Christmas Parade
The Parade steps off from Chesterton Middle School, heads east on Broadway, south on Calumet, and west on Porter Avenue to the Brown Mansion. More than 30 local organizations are represented in the Parade!

6pm-8:30pm
Santa's House in Thomas Centennial Park
Santa will be collecting Christmas wish lists from Duneland boys and girls! Visitors to Santa will be gifted with coloring books and crayons.
***Santa will also be in his House every Saturday leading up to Christmas from 10am-Noon, and again from 1pm-3pm.

VALPARAISO | The public is invited to "Symphony Under the Stars," a free concert featuring the Northwest Indiana Symphony Orchestra at 7:30 Thursday at Central Park Plaza, 64 Lafayette St.

Under the direction of Kirk Muspratt -- music director and conductor, the concert will have something for everyone. The orchestra's selections will feature light classical, pops and patriotic music as well as music from Broadway musicals, TV and movies.

In the event of rain, the performance will move to Chesterton High School, 2125 S. 11th St. Watch for updates on the Porter County Community Foundation's Facebook page or visit portercountyfoundation.org.

status_message:
Mother's Day is just around the corner, and what better way to show your mom you love her than by letting the whole world know?! OK, so your mom won't be made famous worldwide, but she could become famous around town! Curious? Just send an essay to celebrate@nwi.com telling us why your mom is the best for our Mother's Day Contest! All entries are due by May 9. We'll share the essays on our Community sites, and the winner will receive some pretty awesome prizes.

The Rules:
1. Essays should be 200 words or less
2. Don't forget to add your names, cities you live in, email address and contact number

Just a reminder that the Nine Span Bridge demolition begins Monday. 
The approved Indiana Department of Transportation detour for northbound traffic will be to go east on Interstate 80/94, north on Ind. 912 (Cline Avenue), and west on U.S. 20 (Michigan Street). Southbound traffic will travel east on U.S. 20 (Michigan Street), south on Ind. 912 (Cline Avenue), and west on I-80/94. 
The new bridge is expected to open by the end of the year.

Are you the lucky winner??

Hoosier Lotto ticket purchased in Highland 
wins $10 million jackpot

INDIANAPOLIS - One ticket purchased for Saturday night's Hoosier Lotto drawing matched all six numbers and won a jackpot worth $10 million.

The winning numbers drawn were: 5-10-17-21-23-28.

This marks the second Hoosier Lotto jackpot hit of 2012. One winning ticket purchased at a Shelbyville retailer won a $34.5 million jackpot back on Feb. 18.

Hoosier Lottery officials remind players to check their numbers carefully and to sign the back of their tickets immediately. The person holding the winning ticket should contact Hoosier Lottery Customer Service for details on how to claim their prize at (800) 955-6886.

More details will be released as information becomes available

status_message: Twin brothers Billy and Lucas Ramsey celebrated their 11th birthday on Friday, April 13 and it was a celebration they will never forget. Denver Broncos quarterback Peyton Manning made a special appearance at Douglas MacArthur as the result of the Ramsey family winning the Get Peyton on Your Turf sweepstakes sponsored by Meijer and Gatorade. Manning spoke to students about living an active and healthy lifestyle and the importance of working hard in school at the all school assembly. "It is never too early to start setting dreams and setting goals," Manning said.

GARY | Quentin Smith describes the new George Lucas film "Red Tails" as "a movie meant to keep an important story and message alive for future generations to know and learn from."

Smith, 93, is part of that story being shared on screens around the country this week, and he says the timing for the film's national release couldn't be more ideal.

"There's going to be plenty more special showings of this movie for the Monday Martin Luther King Jr. holiday," Smith said after attending an advance VIP studio screening Sunday afternoon at Kerasotes Showplace ICON Theatre on Roosevelt Road in Chicago.

"It's a movie that matters."

status_message:
VALPARAISO | The family that entered the Goodwill store Saturday seemed like any other, workers said.

They were polite and looked like regular folks, but what they did was selfless and extraordinary, Erika Miller said.

Miller, district manager of the Goodwill Industries stores in Northwest Indiana, wasn't at the store at 2109 Calumet Ave. when it happened. But employees told her of the family's generosity.

"They came in and had a stack of Christmas card envelopes, and that's what they started passing out to everybody," she said. "One of the ladies that had been handed one of the cards came up to the register and opened it, and it was a Christmas card and there was money. It said 'Merry Christmas Angel.'"
link_name: Anonymous family shares wealth, happiness with Valpo Goodwill shoppers

status_message:
Wave with nwi.com
Google Wavers in #nwindiana and #indiana, join @chrislkeller's crowdsource and crowd-aggregation experiment leading up to Obama's speech tonight.

In a speech at West Point tonight, President Barack Obama is scheduled to reveal a buildup of as many as 30,000 U.S. troops in Afghanistan.
Join members of nwi.com and the Northwest Indiana community in gathering background material, links, tweets, video and other assorted pieces of information in the hours leading up to the President's speech.

Then tonight, during the 7 p.m. speech, share your reaction here. I envision this as a crowdsource/crowd-aggregation experiment followed by a chat.
Comments are on the record, which hopefully won't sway people from voicing their opinion, and will help foster a spirited, focused debate.

If you would like a Google Wave invite, many of us have some left. Email me and I can put you in contact with others.

Chris Keller
